b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Flat EV fees outpace gas taxes by 200-300%"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"10% of new cars are electric—yet bear disproportionate costs"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Infrastructure math ignores EVs’ long-term public health savings"}]]}]]}]}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["Electric vehicle owners in at least a dozen states may soon pay ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"$$200 to $250 annually"}]," in new fees—",["$","strong",null,{"children":"two to three times"}]," what the average gas-powered car contributes via federal fuel taxes. The justification? Funding crumbling roads. The problem? The math is a political sleight of hand.\nGas taxes, currently ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"18.4 cents per gallon federally"}],", generate about ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"$$70–$100 per year"}]," for the typical driver, according to ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.cbo.gov/publication/57021","children":"Congressional Budget Office data"}],". Yet EVs, which account for ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-07-12/us-electric-vehicle-sales-hit-record-7-2-in-q2-2023","children":"roughly 10% of new car sales"}]," and weigh far less (reducing road wear), face flat fees that assume they’re the budget black hole. Lawmakers frame this as ‘user pays’ equity, but it’s more like ‘user ",["$","em",null,{"children":"over"}],"pays’—especially when EVs already ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.ucsusa.org/resources/cleaner-cars-cleaner-air","children":"deliver $1.7 billion annually in public health benefits"}]," by cutting tailpipe pollution.\nThe timing is particularly tone-deaf. With federal EV tax credits finally gaining traction and automakers like ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/ford-tesla-deal-gives-blue-oval-customers-access-supercharger-network-2023-05-25/","children":"Tesla and Ford"}]," racing to expand charging networks, these fees risk ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"undermining adoption just as it hits critical mass"}],". Worse, they ignore the ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"second-order cost"}],": if EVs stall at 15% market share because of punitive policies, the U.S. misses its ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.epa.gov/regulations-emissions-vehicles-and-engines/epa-and-dot-propose-new-emissions-standards-light","children":"2030 emissions targets"}],"—and gas drivers foot the bill for ",["$","em",null,{"children":"those"}]," failures later."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/ev-owners-face-250-feeswhile-gas-drivers-pay-a-fra/subtitle.jpg","alt":"When ‘fairness’ means charging clean cars for roads they barely damage","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"When ‘fairness’ means charging clean cars for roads they barely damage"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The real kicker? ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"EVs already pay for roads—just differently."}]," Registration fees, sales taxes, and (in some states) ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"per-kWh charges"}]," cover infrastructure. The issue isn’t that EVs freeload; it’s that gas taxes, unchanged since 1993, no longer reflect inflation or fuel efficiency. Instead of modernizing the system—say, with ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"mileage-based fees"}]," that apply to ",["$","em",null,{"children":"all"}]," vehicles—lawmakers are slapping EVs with a ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"regressive surcharge"}]," that treats them like luxury items.\nIndustry players see the hypocrisy. ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://rivian.com/policy","children":"Rivian’s policy team"}]," notes that ‘flat fees disproportionately hurt rural EV owners,’ who often drive longer distances but lack charging alternatives. Meanwhile, gas guzzlers in ","$L14"," (now 80% of U.S. sales) keep paying pennies per mile while doing ","$L15"," of a Model 3.\nThe broader signal is clear: ","$L16"," States like ","$L17",", which have passed similar fees, also happen to be ","$L18",". Coincidence? Maybe. But when ‘infrastructure funding’ starts looking like ","$L19",", even fiscal conservatives should ask: ","$L1a","\nFor now, the fees are a ","$L1b",". If they stick, expect two outcomes: ","$L1c",", and a ","$L1d"," that make cross-country road trips a bureaucratic nightmare. The only winners? Lobbyists and the status quo."]}]]}]
